---
import Prose from "./Prose.astro";
import "./demo.css";
---

<div class="grid gap-14 p-xl">
  <p class="demo-intro text-sm">
    Wraps rendered markdown or rich HTML content and applies the type scale to child
    elements. Use around <code>&lt;Content /&gt;</code> from Astro content collections
    or any block of semantic HTML. Also available as a standalone <code>.prose</code> class.
  </p>

  <section>
    <h3 class="demo-section-label">Full Example</h3>
    <div class="demo-specimen" style="border: none; padding: 0;">
      <Prose>
        <h1>Solidarity in the Digital Age</h1>
        <p>
          When Kickstarter United filed for a union election with the NLRB in early 2020, it
          became one of the first recognized unions at a major tech company. The effort proved
          that white-collar tech workers could organize just like any other workforce &mdash;
          and win.
        </p>

        <h2>Why Workers Organize</h2>
        <p>
          Unions exist because individual workers have little leverage against large employers.
          Through <strong>collective bargaining</strong>, workers negotiate as equals. A union
          contract covers wages, benefits, working conditions, and establishes a grievance
          process so no one has to face management alone.
        </p>
        <p>
          As the saying goes: <em>together we bargain, alone we beg.</em>
        </p>

        <h3>Key Benefits of Union Membership</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Legally binding contracts that protect wages and benefits</li>
          <li>A democratic voice in workplace decisions</li>
          <li>Protection against unjust termination</li>
          <li>Access to grievance and arbitration procedures</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Steps to Forming a Union</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Talk to your coworkers about shared workplace concerns</li>
          <li>Connect with an established union for guidance and support</li>
          <li>Build majority support through authorization cards</li>
          <li>File for an NLRB election and vote to certify</li>
          <li>Negotiate your first contract with management</li>
        </ol>

        <blockquote>
          <p>
            An injury to one is an injury to all. The labor movement is built on the
            principle that when we stand together, every worker is stronger.
          </p>
        </blockquote>

        <h4>Understanding Your Rights</h4>
        <p>
          Under the <a href="#">National Labor Relations Act</a>, all workers have the right
          to organize, join a union, and bargain collectively. It is illegal for employers to
          retaliate against workers for union activity. If you believe your rights have been
          violated, you can file a charge with the NLRB.
        </p>

        <hr />

        <h2>OPEIU Local 153</h2>
        <p>
          OPEIU Local 153 represents workers throughout New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania,
          and Connecticut in fields ranging from social services and legal aid to higher
          education and healthcare. The local is part of the Office and Professional Employees
          International Union, which has represented white-collar workers since 1945.
        </p>

        <p>
          For more details, see the <code>union-resources</code> directory or run
          <code>bun run build</code> to generate the full site.
        </p>

        <h3>Membership by Sector</h3>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Sector</th>
              <th>Workers</th>
              <th>Region</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Higher Education</td>
              <td>Faculty &amp; staff</td>
              <td>NY, NJ</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Healthcare</td>
              <td>Nurses &amp; technicians</td>
              <td>NY, CT</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Legal Aid</td>
              <td>Attorneys &amp; paralegals</td>
              <td>NY</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Technology</td>
              <td>Engineers &amp; designers</td>
              <td>NY</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <p><small>Data reflects OPEIU Local 153 membership sectors. Figures are approximate.</small></p>
      </Prose>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h3 class="demo-section-label">Max Line Length</h3>
    <div class="grid gap-xl">
      <div class="demo-specimen">
        <code class="demo-label text-sm">maxLineLength (default: true = 65ch)</code>
        <Prose>
          <p>
            This prose block is capped at 65 characters per line. Long-form content is easier
            to read when lines are kept to a comfortable measure. The default works well for
            articles and blog posts.
          </p>
        </Prose>
      </div>
      <div class="demo-specimen">
        <code class="demo-label text-sm">maxLineLength={false}</code>
        <Prose maxLineLength={false}>
          <p>
            With line length uncapped, prose fills the entire available width. This is useful
            when the layout container already constrains the width, such as inside the page grid's
            CONTENT column.
          </p>
        </Prose>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>
